      <h1 id="ciphers_font">Steganography</h1>
      <p> Steganography is the practice of concealing a file, message, image, or video within another file, message, image, or video. <br>
      Whereas cryptography is the practice of protecting the contents of a message alone, steganography is concerned with concealing the fact that
      a secret message is being sent as well as concealing the contents of the message.</p>
      <p>The <span id="bold">advantage of steganography</span> over cryptography alone is that the intended secret message does not attract attention to itself as an
        object of scrutiny. </p>
      <p>The first recorded use of the term was in 1499 by Johannes Trithemius in his Steganographia, a treatise on cryptography and steganography,
        disguised as a book on magic. Generally, the hidden messages appear to be (or to be part of) something else:
        images, articles, shopping lists, or some other cover text. For example, the hidden message may be in invisible ink between
        the visible lines of a private letter. </p>

